MOSCOW – Germany were stunned 1-0 by Mexico in the opening game of their World Cup defence on Sunday in Luzhniki Stadium Moscow. Hirving Lozano finished off a sharp counter-attack that exposed the ragged defending that the four-times winners had displayed in their warm-up games. MEXICO DOES IT!
		
		Lozano's first-half goal holds up as #ElTri defeats Germany 1-0 in their FIFA World Cup opener. pic.twitter.com/KD5aSHTCWg Germany's defence had looked stretched to breaking point on several occasions in the opening half-hour and it was no surprise when Javier Hernandez again left Mats Hummels for dead to play in Lozano, who cut inside Mesut Ozil and smashed the ball low into the corner to release an explosion of noise. READ: Germany 'keeper Neuer makes first start for eight months Germany came close to levelling late in the half when a Toni Kroos' free kick touched on to the bar by goalkeeper Guillermo Ochoa, and they gradually took command once Marco Reus joined the fray after an hour and introduced some pace to their attack. Full time: Germany 0 - 1 Mexico!
		
